data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` gives unhelpful failure messages like "Expected: True, Actual: False."

Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Clear failure message: "Expected:<3>. Actual:<0>."
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Verifies a condition holds for every element
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Not all users are active");

    // Check a specific item exists
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "No admin user found");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)`** — shows both values on failure instead of just `True/False`
- **`CollectionAssert`** — purpose-built for collections:
  - `AllItemsAreNotNull(collection)`
  - `AllItemsAreUnique(collection)`
  - `Contains(collection, item)`
  - `AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same elements, same order
  - `AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — same elements, any order
  - `IsSubsetOf(subset, superset)`
- **Always add a message string** to `Assert.IsTrue` when you must use it — otherwise failures are unreadable

**One more tip:** avoid `users.Single()` in tests — it throws an unhelpful `InvalidOperationException` instead of a proper test failure. Prefer `Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(...))` or `users.FirstOrDefault()` + `Assert.IsNotNull()`.
